text.__SUMMARY__:
Corymbia kombolgiensis, commonly known as the scarp gum or the paper-fruited bloodwood, is a member of the genus Corymbia native to the Northern TerritoryThe tree typically grows to a height of 12 metres (39 ft) and forms a lignotuber. The bark is grey rough, flaky and tessellated on the trunk and smooth creamy white to
orange-brown sometimes powdery elsewhere.
